<p>
The stemmers for these three Scandinavian languages are all very simple,
and quite similar to each other. But between the languages there is a difference
in which endings can be removed without difficulty, even though the endings
are very similar. For example, in Norwegian
the ending <B><I>ede</I></B> can be removed safely, but not in Danish.
</p>

<p>
The Scandinavian languages have a noun ending corresponding to the definite
article (<I>the</I> in English).  This ending cannot always be removed
with certainty. In Swedish, for example, the <B><I>en</I></B> form is removed,
and the <b><i>et</i></b> form in some cases, but not the <B><I>t</I></B> or
<B><I>n</I></B> form,
</p>

